      h1 hack.css - the CSS framework for hackers

      p As what you can see, this website is proudly using hack.css.

      h2 About

      p As many hackers enjoy the readability of markdown code, some stylings in hack.css are exactly the way markdown is.

      ul
        li conquer the world
        li rule the web
        li copy the code

      p 
        a(target="_blank" href="https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/") kinda cool, huh?

      p hack.css is a superset of <a target="_blank" href="https://github.com/mrcoles/markdown-css">markdown.css</a> with more common UI utilities plugged in.


      :marked
        ```js
        // some random code
        import Vue from 'vue'
        import App from './app'

        new Vue({
          el: '#app',
          render: h => h(App)
        })
        ```
      p
        | The code looks not bad, you can use <a target="_blank" href="http://prismjs.com/">prism.js</a> to make it colorful.

      h2 How to use?

      p Install via npm by running <code>npm install -S hack</code> and load it with your preferred pre-processor.

      p You can also simply hot-link the url of css file.

      p The last step is to add <code>.hack</code> class to your body element.

      :marked
        ```html
        <head>
          <link href="/path/to/hack.css" ref="stylesheet" />
        </head>
        <body class="hack">
          ...
        </body>
        ```

      h2 User guide

      h3 Basic

      p Use <code>.container</code> to centerlize to main content.

      p User <strong>flexbox</strong> to make layouts,  hack.css uses <a href="https://github.com/1000ch/grd" target="_blank">grd.css</a> to provide a flexbox based grid system.

